org.gitlab.api

Class GitlabIssue.Query

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.gitlab.api.GitlabIssue.Query
  • Enclosing class:
    GitlabIssue

    public static class GitlabIssue.Query
extends java.lang.Object
    This extends GitlabQuery and supports query global GitlabIssues with searching scope and range. Build this query with setters and call query() to execute query.

    Gitlab Web API: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/api/issues.html#list-issues

    GET /issues

        public GitlabIssue.Query withAssigneeId(int assigneeId)
        Returns a query that returns issues assigned to the given user id. This should not be used with withAssigneeUsernames simultaneously. None returns unassigned issues. Any returns issues with an assignee.

        assigneeId - id of the assignee
        Returns:
        this GitlabIssue.ProjectQuery with given assignee

        public GitlabIssue.Query withAssigneeUsernames(java.util.List<java.lang.String> assigneeUsernames)
        Returns a query that returns issues assigned to the given username. This should not be used with withAssigneeId simultaneously. In GitLab CE, the assignee_username array should only contain a single value. Otherwise, an invalid parameter error is returned.
        Parameters:
        assigneeUsernames - id of the assignee
        Returns:
        this GitlabIssue.ProjectQuery with given assignees

      • withScope

        public GitlabIssue.Query withScope(java.lang.String scope)
        Returns a query that returns issues for given scope. Scope can be any of: created_by_me, assigned_to_me or all. Defaults to created_by_me. For versions before 11.0, use the now deprecated created-by-me or assigned-to-me scopes instead.
        Parameters:
        scope - different scope in gitlab
        Returns:
